'''Abel Eduardo Balbo''' {{IPA|[a.<U+02C8><U+03B2>el e.<U+02C8><U+00F0>wa<U+027E>.<U+00F0>o <U+02C8><U+03B2>al.<U+03B2>o]}} (born [[June 1]], [[1966]], in [[Empalme Villa Constituci<U+00F3>n]], [[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]]) is a former [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[football (soccer)|football]] [[striker]], the all-time leading foreign goalscorer in [[Italy]]'s [[Serie A]].

On the club level, Balbo played for [[Newell's Old Boys]] (1987-88), [[Club Atl<U+00E9>tico River Plate|River Plate]] (1988-89), before moving to Italy and [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] (1989-93), [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] (1993-98 and 2000-02), [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] (1998-99), and [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]. He played four games for [[Boca Juniors]] before finally retiring. He scored a total of 138 goals in Serie A; his best seasons came in 1990-91 for Udiense and 1994-95 for Roma, with 22 goals in each of them.

For [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], Balbo scored 11 goals in 37 [[cap (sport)|caps]], and played at the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]], the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]], the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]s, the [[Copa Am<U+00E9>rica 1989|1989]] and [[Copa Am<U+00E9>rica 1995|1995 Copas Am<U+00E9>rica]]. At the 1995 tournament in [[Uruguay]], Balbo partnered [[Gabriel Batistuta]] in attack, and scored a goal against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil's]] [[Claudio Taffarel]] in a quarterfinal game that Argentina lost in a [[penalty shootout]] after Brazilian striker [[Tulio Costa]] famously scored the equalizer with 10 minutes remaining in the match after clearly controlling the ball with his arm.

After his retirement, Balbo eventually became a musician by performing songs in [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].

